04600nam a22006975i 9780824861995DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20012001hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248619957 a10.1515/97808248619952doi  a(DE-B1597)483758  a(OCoLC)923490587  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aDS793.Y45 -- D63 2001eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a951/.1  aZI 67052rvk0(DE-625)rvk/156533:1 aDodgen, Randall A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aControlling the Dragon :bConfucian Engineers and the Yellow River in Late Imperial China /cRandall A. Dodgen. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Evolution of the Yellow River Control System in Late Imperial China, 1495–1835 -- t2. Rising Waters -- t3. Confucian Engineers -- t4. The Xiangfu Flood and the Siege of Kaifeng, 1841–1842 -- t5. The Taoyuan Flood and the Zhongmou Debacle, 1842–1845 -- t6. A Change of Course, 1844–1855 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tCharacter Glossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Yellow River has long been viewed as a symbol of China's cultural and political development, its management traditionally held as a gauge of dynastic power. For centuries, the country's early rulers employed a defensive approach to the river by building dikes and diversion channels to protect fields and population centers from flooding. This situation changed dramatically after the Yuan (1260-1368) emperors constructed the Grand Canal, which linked the North China Plain and the capital at Beijing with the Yangtze Valley. One of the most ambitious imperial undertakings of any age, by the turn of the nineteenth century the water system had become a complex network of locks, spillways, and dikes stretching eight hundred kilometers from the mountains in western Henan to the Yellow Sea. Controlling the Dragon examines Yellow River engineering from two perspectives. The first looks at long-term efforts to manage the river starting in the early Ming dynasty, at the nature of the bureaucracy created to do the job, and finally focuses on two of the Confucian engineers who served successfully in the decade before the system was abandoned. In the second section, the author chronicles a series of dramatic floods in the 1840s and explores the way politics, environment, and technology interacted to undermine the state's commitment to the Yellow River control system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486199540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824861995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824861995.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK